            <note xml:id="Vol-2-Vol-1-ADD-d8e4" n="1"> Biblical, e.g. 1 Kgs 1:3.</note>
            <note xml:id="Vol-2-Vol-1-ADD-d8e51" n="1"> Biblical, Ex 6:23. אלישבע was Aaron’s wife.</note>
            <note xml:id="Vol-2-Vol-1-ADD-d8e92" n="1"> Biblical, e.g. Exod 15:20. מרים was Moses’ sister. </note>
            <note xml:id="Vol-2-Vol-1-ADD-d8e407" n="1"> This is the feminine form of the biblical מתתיה. It is, however, never mentioned in the Bible, and thus not counted as biblical. For female names derived from male names see vol. 3, Introduction 1.1.2.1, p. 6. </note>
            <note xml:id="Vol-2-Vol-1-ADD-d8e530" n="1"> נחומה is the feminine form of the biblical נחום. It is, however, never mentioned in the Bible, and thus not counted as biblical. For female names derived from male names see vol. 3, Introduction 1.1.2.1, p. 6. </note>
            <note xml:id="Vol-2-Vol-1-ADD-d8e592" n="1"> In the Bible שלום is recorded only as a man’s name (one of the last kings of Israel, e.g. 2 Kgs 15:10). </note>
            <note xml:id="Vol-2-Vol-1-ADD-d8e1129" n="1"> Biblical, Exod 1:15. שפרה was a Jewish midwife at the time of the Exodus. The form שפירה is probably a variation and indicates how the name was pronounced during the Second Temple period. It means basically the same (quality, beauty). </note>
            <note xml:id="Vol-2-Vol-1-ADD-d8e1175" n="1"> Biblical, e.g. Gen. 17:15. שרה was Abraham’s wife. </note>
